05246nam a22007815i 9780228009818DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280098187 a10.1515/97802280098182doi  a(DE-B1597)656738  a(OCoLC)1268549111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aML3563.3b.L39 2022 7aSOC0080402bisacsh04a780.97109/0332231 aLaxer, Daniel Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aListening to the Fur Trade :bSoundways and Music in the British North American Fur Trade, 1760–1840 /cDaniel Robert Laxer. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b13 photos, 3 maps, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Early Canada / Avant le Canada ;v300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tSpecial Terms -- tIntroduction -- tWith a Bang: Gunpowder and Firearms -- tMusical Encounters -- tMilitary Instruments and “Turned” Drums -- tDances of Diplomacy -- tSoundways from Montreal to La Cloche -- tPaddling Songs; Chansons D’aviron -- tIndigenous Hunting and Healing Songs -- tMusic of the Trading Posts -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs fur traders were driven across northern North America by economic motivations, the landscape over which they plied their trade was punctuated by sound: shouting, singing, dancing, gunpowder, rattles, jingles, drums, fiddles, and – very occasionally – bagpipes. Fur trade interactions were, in a word, noisy. Daniel Laxer unearths traces of music, performance, and other intangible cultural phenomena long since silenced, allowing us to hear the fur trade for the first time.Listening to the Fur Trade uses the written record, oral history, and material culture to reveal histories of sound and music in an era before sound recording. The trading post was a noisy nexus, populated by a polyglot crowd of highly mobile people from different national, linguistic, religious, cultural, and class backgrounds. They found ways to interact every time they met, and facilitating material interests and survival went beyond the simple exchange of goods. Trust and good relations often entailed gift-giving: reciprocity was performed with dances, songs, and firearm salutes. Indigenous protocols of ceremony and treaty-making were widely adopted by fur traders, who supplied materials and technologies that sometimes changed how these ceremonies sounded. Within trading companies, masters and servants were on opposite ends of the social ladder but shared songs in the canoes and lively dances during the long winters at the trading posts.While the fur trade was propelled by economic and political interests, Listening to the Fur Trade uncovers the songs and ceremonies of First Nations people, the paddling songs of the voyageurs, and the fiddle music and step-dancing at the trading posts that provided its pulse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFur tradezCanadaxHistoryy18th century. 0aFur tradezCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aFur tradersxSongs and musicxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Canadian Studies.2bisacsh  aFiddle.  aFrench Voyageurs.  aIndigenous dances.  aMetis.  aMontreal merchants.  aStep-dancing.  aceremonies.  acommercial compacts.  aearly Canadian commerce.  aeconomy.  ainstruments.  aintangible cultural heritage.  ajigging.  amusical interactions.  apractices.  apre-Confederation.  asound-making.  atrading posts.  atraditional.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe